<taxonomicNameLabel box="[769,843,1087,1108]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be easily distinguished from its African congeners by small size and a highly contrasting colour pattern (
<figureCitation box="[159,220,1145,1167]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[151,184,1390,1412]" captionTargetBox="[151,1057,207,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-69@2.[151,1057,207,1381]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1: Aphelocheirus aschalewi nov.sp., habitus of brachypterous male (holotype); legs omitted." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5038840" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5038840/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[244,467,1145,1166]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">Aphelocheirus debilis</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[521,653,1145,1166]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">A. kumbanus</emphasis>
, both only known in the macropterous female, possess a more strongly produced forehead (see 
<bibRefCitation author="LINNAVUORI R" box="[734,924,1174,1196]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142" pagination="89 - 91" refId="ref1976" refString="LINNAVUORI R. (1975): On the genus Aphelochirus (Heteroptera, Naucoridae) of tropical Africa. - Notulae entomologicae 55: 89 - 91." type="journal article" year="1975">LINNAVUORI 1975</bibRefCitation>
: figs 2a, 3a). Experience with Asian species of 
<emphasis box="[500,646,1203,1224]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">Aphelocheirus</emphasis>
has shown that the head shape does not vary among wing morphs of the same species. The forewing remnants of 
<emphasis box="[908,1058,1233,1254]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">A. schoudeteni</emphasis>
are very small, elongate and widely distant from each other (
<bibRefCitation author="LINNAVUORI R" box="[775,966,1262,1284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142" pagination="89 - 91" refId="ref1976" refString="LINNAVUORI R. (1975): On the genus Aphelochirus (Heteroptera, Naucoridae) of tropical Africa. - Notulae entomologicae 55: 89 - 91." type="journal article" year="1975">LINNAVUORI 1975</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1a), while those of 
<emphasis box="[306,408,1291,1313]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">A. corbeti</emphasis>
meet each other at body midline (
<bibRefCitation author="POISSON R" box="[766,916,1291,1313]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142" pagination="154 - 170" refId="ref2038" refString="POISSON R. (1955): Sur quelques Hemipteres aquatiques de l'Afrique orientale et descriptions d'especes nouvelles. - Annali del Museo civico di storia naturale Giacomo Doria 68: 154 - 170." type="journal article" year="1955">POISSON 1955</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 13). The size of the forewings is intermediate in 
<taxonomicName authority="Zettel, 2021" authorityName="Zettel" authorityYear="2021" box="[549,678,1321,1342]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelocheiridae" genus="Aphelocheirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aschalewi" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis box="[549,678,1321,1342]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">A. aschalewi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[684,758,1321,1342]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authority="Zettel, 2021" authorityName="Zettel" authorityYear="2021" box="[929,1058,1321,1342]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelocheiridae" genus="Aphelocheirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aschalewi" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis box="[929,1058,1321,1342]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">A. aschalewi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[151,227,1351,1372]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, most of all the parameres, resemble those of 
<emphasis box="[702,804,1350,1371]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">A. corbeti</emphasis>
, suggesting a close relationship, however, the apices of both parameres are broader in 
<taxonomicName authority="Zettel, 2021" authorityName="Zettel" authorityYear="2021" box="[797,927,1379,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelocheiridae" genus="Aphelocheirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aschalewi" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis box="[797,927,1379,1401]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">A. aschalewi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[934,1008,1380,1401]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
than in 
<emphasis box="[177,278,1409,1430]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">A. corbeti</emphasis>
(comp. 
<figureCitation box="[361,448,1408,1431]" captionStart="Figs 2-8" captionStartId="3.[151,191,967,989]" captionTargetBox="[156,1059,371,939]" captionTargetId="figure-340@3.[154,1065,369,942]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 2-8: Aphelocheirus aschalewi nov.sp.: (2) mesosternum, lateral view; (3) apex of propleuron, ventral view; (4) parandria and aedeagus, dorsal view; (5, 6) right paramere in dorsal (5) and approximately ventral view (6); (7, 8) left paramere in dorsal (7) and ventral view (8)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5038848" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5038848/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">Figs 5–8</figureCitation>
with 
<bibRefCitation author="POISSON R" box="[507,653,1408,1430]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142" pagination="154 - 170" refId="ref2038" refString="POISSON R. (1955): Sur quelques Hemipteres aquatiques de l'Afrique orientale et descriptions d'especes nouvelles. - Annali del Museo civico di storia naturale Giacomo Doria 68: 154 - 170." type="journal article" year="1955">POISSON 1955</bibRefCitation>
: figs 13B, C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1058,1446,1497]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1142">E t y m o l o g y: The species name honours Aschalew Haile Lakew for his important role in establishing and conducting the LARIMA Project.</paragraph>
